# =============================================================================
#  Drain Man Inc — Environment Variables (template)
# =============================================================================
#
#  WHAT THIS FILE IS
#    A committed, secret-free template listing every environment variable this
#    project understands. Copy it to .env.local and fill in real values there.
#    .env.local is gitignored — NEVER commit real values.
#
#  LOCAL SETUP
#    1.  cp .env.example .env.local
#    2.  Edit .env.local and set the value(s) below.
#    3.  Restart the dev server:  npm run dev   (Next.js only reads env at boot)
#
#  PRODUCTION (Vercel)
#    Set the same variable(s) in:
#      Project → Settings → Environment Variables
#    then redeploy (env changes only take effect on a new deployment).
#
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  CONTACT_WEBHOOK_URL                              [ server-only · optional* ]
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  The ONLY environment variable the running app actually reads.
#
#  The contact / booking form (components/booking/BookingForm.tsx) POSTs to
#  app/api/contact/route.ts, which validates the submission and forwards it as
#  JSON to THIS url. The destination is meant to be an automation "catch hook"
#  that turns the submission into an email to the company (admin@drainmaninc.com).
#  It is a webhook-to-email bridge — NOT a live calendar.
#
#  JSON payload that gets POSTed to this url:
#    { name, phone, email, service, city, timing, message, source, submittedAt }
#
#  Get a url from any service that accepts a JSON POST, e.g.:
#    • Zapier    — "Webhooks by Zapier → Catch Hook"  →  Gmail / Email action
#                  (note: Webhooks is a paid Zapier feature)
#    • Make.com  — "Custom webhook" trigger           →  Email module  (free tier)
#    • Formspree — your project endpoint url           (accepts JSON; free tier)
#
#  *OPTIONAL in development: if this is empty/unset the form still works — the
#   API logs the payload to the server console and returns success, but sends NO
#   email. REQUIRED in production for leads to actually be delivered.
#
#  SCOPE: server-only. Do NOT rename it with a NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix — the url is
#  the only secret, and a NEXT_PUBLIC_ var is shipped to every visitor's browser.
#
#  Example value:
#    CONTACT_WEBHOOK_URL=https://hooks.zapier.com/hooks/catch/1234567/abcdefg/
#
CONTACT_WEBHOOK_URL=


# =============================================================================
#  The entries below are NOT read by the app today. They are listed for
#  awareness only and are intentionally left commented out. Setting them has
#  NO effect unless you ALSO make the code change noted for each.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL                             [ public · NOT WIRED YET ]
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  The site's canonical production origin, used for SEO metadataBase, the
#  OpenGraph url, sitemap.xml entries, and robots.txt. Today this value is
#  HARDCODED as "https://drainmaninc.com" in three files that are kept in sync
#  by hand:
#      app/layout.tsx   (metadataBase + OpenGraph url)
#      app/sitemap.ts
#      app/robots.ts
#  To drive it from this variable instead, those three files must be refactored
#  to read process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL (defaulting to the current value).
#  Until that refactor exists, uncommenting this does nothing.
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL=https://drainmaninc.com

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  PEXELS_KEY                              [ build-time tooling · NOT RUNTIME ]
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  Used ONLY by the optional stock-photo fetch recipe documented in
#  BUILD_CONTRACT.md. The shipped site uses local images in public/images/ and
#  never reads this at runtime. You only need it if you re-fetch new stock
#  photos via that script. Get a free key at https://www.pexels.com/api/.
#
# PEXELS_KEY=your-free-pexels-api-key
